    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-10-12T21:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-10-12T21:30:00-05:00" n="414"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                <head>414. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Saudi Arabia</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d414fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, RG 59, Central Files 1964-66, <gloss target="#t_POL1"
                            >POL</gloss> 7 SAUD. Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MGC1"
                            >Moore</persName>; cleared by Officer in Charge of Somali Affairs Peter
                        C. Walker, Director of the Office of Northern African Affairs John F. Root,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BDC1">Bergus</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_AALRJ1">Atherton</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CSJ1"
                            >Campbell</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_SHM1">Symmes</persName>;
                        and approved by <persName corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName>. Repeated to
                        Cairo, Taiz, London, Aden, and <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-10-12T22:30:00-04:00">October 12, 1966, 10:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>64986. (Following <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_Noforn1">Noforn</gloss>, based on uncleared memcon, subject
                    revision on review.) Following principal subjects discussed during Saudi Deputy
                    Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_SSO1">Saqqaf</persName>’s call on
                    Secretary October 11.</p>
                <p>1. Yemen. <persName corresp="#p_SSO1">Saqqaf</persName> convinced <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> does not want solve problem or leave Yemen at
                    least before British departure from Aden in two years. (Secretary noted <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> still tells us they want solution and their
                    attitude in Yemen not affected by developments in Aden.) <persName
                        corresp="#p_SSO1">Saqqaf</persName> believes Kuwait mediation efforts of no
                    avail. Within Yemen, none of groups involved seems any longer satisfied with
                    circumstances. Many Yemenis dying all parts of country from sickness and hunger.
                    Fighting continuing in some areas where <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> is
                    invading “royalist regions”.</p>
                <p>Secretary queried if, following Kuwaiti efforts, putting Yemen problem into UN
                    would be helpful. <persName corresp="#p_SSO1">Saqqaf</persName> demurred noting
                    none of parties had mentioned subject in the <gloss target="#t_UNGA1"
                        >UNGA</gloss> speeches and little progress to be expected since Yemen
                    Republic was UN member.</p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of other subjects.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
